    "rationale": "This example demonstrates the decarbonylation of an aldehyde to its corresponding alkane. The substrate, 1-phenylcyclopentane-1-carbaldehyde, possesses a quaternary carbon adjacent to the formyl group, which is a classic and robust substrate type for this transformation. The removal of the -CHO group to form phenylcyclopentane is unambiguous and clearly illustrates the carbon-carbon bond cleavage characteristic of the Tsuji-Wilkinson reaction, mediated by a rhodium catalyst. The product retains the core spirocyclic-aromatic structure, highlighting the specific loss of the carbonyl group as carbon monoxide.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "The substrate is a non-trivial aldehyde with a quaternary center, which helps distinguish it from simple aliphatic or aromatic aldehydes (like benzaldehyde) that might be decarbonylated under various other, more generic conditions. This specificity targets the Rh-catalyzed mechanism and avoids overlap with broader aldehyde reduction or decarbonylation methods.",
    "reagents_text": "Tris(triphenylphosphine)rhodium(I) chloride (Wilkinson's catalyst)",
    "conditions_text": "Heat (e.g., refluxing toluene or xylene)"
  }
}
